con&s;cience, and to lead a virtuous and ho|nourable,
at lea&s;t an innoffen&s;ive and in|nocent,
life. Of &s;uch a man only it can
<PB N="276" REF="285">
be &s;aid, that <HI>doing the&s;e things he &s;hall ne|ver
be moved.</HI> So great is the power of
con&s;cience over every human being, that
the remembrance of crime$ never fails to
overthrow tranquillity of mind. Be a&s;|&s;ured,
that he who defrauds his neighbour,
who has en&s;nared the innocent, has viola|ted
this tru&s;t, or betrayed his friend, &s;hall
never enjoy within him&s;elf undi&s;turbed
