We too often behold per&s;ons, who&s;e prin|ciples,
and who&s;e moral conduct, are in the
main unexceptionable, leading an uncom|fortable
life; through fretfulne&s;s of temper,
peevi&s;hne&s;s of manners, or $ullenne&s;s of
di&s;po&s;ition. There is, therefore, &s;ome di&s;|cipline
to be &s;tudied; there are &s;ome &s;ub&s;i|diary
parts of character to be attended to,
in order to give piety and virtue their full
effect for conferring tranquillity. To the
