per&s;ons are not likely to enjoy much real
comfort. For it is in the daily and fami|liar
intercour&s;e of life, that temper chief|ly
exerts its power, either for promoting
or for di&s;turbing, the tranquillity of our
days. On occa&s;ions when men come clo&s;|e&s;t
together$ if, in&s;tead of meeting in
&s;mooth contact, they rub and grate on
one another, the feelings produced on
both &s;ides are of the mo&s;t offen&s;ive and
