<P>I HAVE thus pointed out what appears
to me the di&s;cipline of religion and wi&s;|dom
for tranquillity of mind. <HI>He that
doth the&s;e things &s;hall never be moved.</HI>&mdash;During
the early periods of life, vivid &s;$n|&s;ations
of plea&s;ure are the &s;ole objects
thought wo$thy of pur&s;uit. Mere ea&s;e and
calmne&s;s are de&s;pi&s;ed, as the portion of
the aged only and the feeble. Some long|er
acquaintance with the world, with its
di&s;appointed hopes and fallacious pl$$|&s;ures,
teaches almo&s;t all men, by degrees,
to wi&s;h for tranquillity and peace. But
