not prone to <HI>to take up reproach again&s;t his
neighbour.</HI></P>
<P>IN the <HI>&s;ixth</HI> and la&s;t place, let me exhort
you not to de&s;ert your friend in danger
of di&s;tre&s;s. Too many there are in the
world, who&s;e attachment to tho&s;e they
call their friends is confined to the day of
their pro&s;perity. As long as that conti|nues,
they are, or appear to be, affection|ate
and cordial. But as &s;oon as their
friends is under a cloud, they begin to
withdraws, and to &s;eparate their intere&s;ts
from his. In friend&s;hip of this &s;ort, the
heart, a&s;&s;uredly, has never had much con|cern.
For the great te&s;t of true friend&s;hip,
is con&s;tancy in the hour of danger, adhe|rence
in the &s;ea&s;on of di&s;tre&s;s.&mdash;When
your friend is calumniated, then is the
time, openly and boldly to e&s;pou&s;e his
cau&s;e. When his &s;ituation is changed, or
his fortunes are falling, then is the time of
<PB N="375" REF="384">
affording prompt and zealous aid. When
&s;ickne&s;s of infirmity occa&s;ion him to be
neglected by others, that is the opportu|nity
which every real friend will &s;eize, of
