<HI>his ighteou&s;ue&s;s comes forth as the light,
and $$s judgement as the noon-day.</HI></P>
<P>It is, accordingly, this &s;teady inflexible
virtue, this regard to principle, &s;uperior to
all cu&s;tom and opinion, which peculiarly
marked the characters of tho&s;e, in any
age, who have &s;hone as &s;aints or heroes;
and has con&s;ecrated their memory to all
po&s;terity. It was this that obtained to
ancient <HI>Enoch</HI> the mo&s;t &s;ingular te&s;timo|ny
of honour from heaven. He conti|nued
<HI>to walk with God,</HI> when the world
apo&s;tati&s;ed from him. He plea&s;ed God,
and was beloved of him; &s;o that, living
<PB N="417" REF="426">
living among &s;inners, he was tran&s;lated to
